House Resolution 237
By: Representative Au of the 50th
A RESOLUTION
1 Recognizing and commending John Suttles; and for other purposes.
2 WHEREAS, John Suttles courageously participated in the historic Bloody Sunday march in
3 Selma, Alabama, on March 7, 1965, at just 16 years old, walking in pursuit of civil rights
4 alongside hundreds of peaceful demonstrators; and
5 WHEREAS, on the day of the march, he wore an army jacket given to him by his uncle,
6 which is now preserved and displayed at a national interpretive center; and
7 WHEREAS, the march, which saw 600 protesters of diverse backgrounds crossing the
8 Edmund Pettus Bridge on their way to Montgomery, stands as a defining moment in the Civil
9 Rights Movement; and
10 WHEREAS, despite being hospitalized as a result of the violence that took place on Bloody
11 Sunday, John Suttles remained undeterred and took part in the subsequent marches from
12 Selma to Montgomery, including the final march that began on March 21 and successfully
13 reached Montgomery on March 24, 1965; and
